Thanks very much.

249
00:15:04,923 --> 00:15:06,413
Welcome to
the Dolphin, sir.

250
00:15:06,458 --> 00:15:08,426
- Are you checking in?
- Mike Enslin.

251
00:15:08,460 --> 00:15:09,688
One night.

252
00:15:09,728 --> 00:15:12,219
And how are we
spelling that today?

253
00:15:12,264 --> 00:15:14,528
- N-S-L-l-N?
- N-S-L-l-N.

254
00:15:14,566 --> 00:15:15,760
Yeah.

255
00:15:21,340 --> 00:15:23,570
Uh, would you excuse me
for a moment, sir?

256
00:15:23,609 --> 00:15:25,338
Sure.

257
00:15:28,447 --> 00:15:31,473
Mr. Dempsey, Mike Enslin's
just checked in.

258
00:15:31,517 --> 00:15:33,985
- Where is he?
- He's over at my desk.

259
00:15:34,019 --> 00:15:36,419
That's fine, Marie.
I'll take care of it.

260
00:15:36,455 --> 00:15:37,820
Okay.

261
00:15:43,228 --> 00:15:45,219
It'll just be a minute,
Mr. Enslin.

262
00:15:45,264 --> 00:15:46,959
(baby crying)

263
00:15:50,302 --> 00:15:52,634
Good evening, sir.
Can I help you with your bag?

264
00:15:52,671 --> 00:15:55,139
- No.
- Very well.

265
00:15:57,042 --> 00:15:59,704
Mr. Enslin,
I'm Gerald Olin,

266
00:15:59,745 --> 00:16:01,508
manager of
the Dolphin.

267
00:16:01,547 --> 00:16:04,482
If there's anything that I can do
for you while you're here...

268
00:16:04,516 --> 00:16:06,780
dinner reservations,
theater tickets,

269
00:16:06,818 --> 00:16:08,547
maybe a Knicks game?
Anything...

270
00:16:08,587 --> 00:16:10,578
just tell me.
I am at your service.

271
00:16:10,622 --> 00:16:13,750
Well, if I can just get the key to 1408,
I can get out of your hair.

272
00:16:13,792 --> 00:16:17,523
Oh, we were thinking
of upgrading you to a penthouse suite.

273
00:16:17,563 --> 00:16:20,088
1408, please.

274
00:16:20,132 --> 00:16:22,259
Insistent,
aren't we?

275
00:16:22,301 --> 00:16:24,166
Could you please
humor me

276
00:16:24,203 --> 00:16:28,196
by coming to my office for a more
private conversation?

277
00:16:28,240 --> 00:16:30,640
- Sure.
- Excellent.

278
00:16:34,746 --> 00:16:37,180
Come in.
Make yourself comfortable.

279
00:16:38,917 --> 00:16:40,748
1408 a smoking room?

280
00:16:40,786 --> 00:16:43,084
As a matter of fact,
it is. Yes.

281
00:16:43,121 --> 00:16:46,522
Good, one less worry in
the watches of the night.

282
00:16:46,558 --> 00:16:48,492
Care for a cigar?

283
00:16:48,527 --> 00:16:50,654
No thank you,
I don't smoke.

284
00:16:50,696 --> 00:16:52,459
Oh this, yeah.
That's...

285
00:16:52,497 --> 00:16:54,931
in case nuclear war
breaks out.

286
00:16:54,967 --> 00:16:56,127
I gave it up
a long time ago.

287
00:16:56,168 --> 00:16:58,033
It's part habit,
part superstition.

288
00:16:58,070 --> 00:16:59,435
It's, you know,
a writer thing.

289
00:16:59,471 --> 00:17:01,234
You do drink,
don't you?

290
00:17:01,273 --> 00:17:03,036
Of course, I just said
I was a writer.

291
00:17:03,075 --> 00:17:06,374
Le Cinquante Sept
Deces, 1939.

292
00:17:06,411 --> 00:17:08,208
Exquisite.

293
00:17:08,247 --> 00:17:10,442
About $800 a bottle,
when you can find it.

294
00:17:10,482 --> 00:17:13,349
I appreciate the bribe,
but I intend on staying in that room.

295
00:17:14,653 --> 00:17:16,712
- How long?
- How long?

296
00:17:17,723 --> 00:17:19,350
My usual is
overnight.

297
00:17:19,391 --> 00:17:21,359
I see.

298
00:17:21,393 --> 00:17:24,226
No one's ever lasted
more than an hour.

299
00:17:24,263 --> 00:17:26,197
(laughs)
Jesus, man.

300
00:17:26,231 --> 00:17:28,290
You ought to shave your eyebrows
and paint your hair gold

301
00:17:28,333 --> 00:17:30,824
if you're gonna try
to sell that spookhouse bullshit.

302
00:17:30,869 --> 00:17:32,302
Otherwise, you'll
scare the children.

303
00:17:32,337 --> 00:17:34,396
Why are you mocking me
when I am genuinely,

304
00:17:34,439 --> 00:17:36,634
to the best of my ability,
trying to help you?

305
00:17:36,675 --> 00:17:38,404
No, you're playing
a little game.

306
00:17:38,443 --> 00:17:40,673
You're selling
the mystique.

307
00:17:40,712 --> 00:17:43,112
But eventually,
we both know

308
00:17:43,148 --> 00:17:45,673
you're gonna give me the key
and I'm gonna go up to the room

309
00:17:45,717 --> 00:17:48,413
and I'm gonna write my story
and your bookings are gonna go up 50%.

310
00:17:48,453 --> 00:17:51,786
Do you mind if my little friend records
our conversation?

311
00:17:54,593 --> 00:17:55,992
I'll take that as a yes.

312
00:17:56,028 --> 00:17:59,429
Sir, you quite
misunderstand the situation.

313
00:17:59,464 --> 00:18:02,763
Now, I know the Dolphin
doesn't have the cachet of the Plaza

314
00:18:02,801 --> 00:18:04,496
or the Carlyle,

315
00:18:04,536 --> 00:18:07,664
but we operate
at 90% capacity.

316
00:18:07,706 --> 00:18:08,866
Always.

317
00:18:08,907 --> 00:18:11,569
And my concern here
is not for the hotel.

318
00:18:11,610 --> 00:18:14,135
My concern here
is not for you.

319
00:18:14,179 --> 00:18:16,443
Frankly, selfishly,

320
00:18:16,481 --> 00:18:19,450
I don't want you
to check into 1408

321
00:18:19,484 --> 00:18:21,816
because I don't want
to clean up the mess.

322
00:18:21,853 --> 00:18:25,254
Now hotels are all
about presentation

323
00:18:25,290 --> 00:18:27,850
and fertile
creature comforts.

324
00:18:27,893 --> 00:18:30,862
My training is
as a manager,

325
00:18:30,896 --> 00:18:32,864
not a coroner.

326
00:18:32,898 --> 00:18:36,197
Under my watch there have
been four deaths... four.

327
00:18:36,234 --> 00:18:38,794
After the last one,
I forbade any guest

328
00:18:38,837 --> 00:18:41,101
from checking
into 1408 ever again.

329
00:18:41,139 --> 00:18:44,472
The last one was David Hide,
orthodontist, manic-depressive.

330
00:18:44,509 --> 00:18:46,636
Slit his wrist,
did a little self-surgery,

331
00:18:46,678 --> 00:18:48,145
turned himself into
a eunuch, right?

332
00:18:48,180 --> 00:18:50,671
Yes. So you've
done your homework.

333
00:18:50,716 --> 00:18:51,842
I'm a professional too.

334
00:18:51,883 --> 00:18:54,784
Well, grievously, in its
95-year existence,

335
00:18:54,820 --> 00:18:57,220
the hotel has seen
seven jumpers,

336
00:18:57,255 --> 00:18:59,280
four overdoses,
five hangings,

337
00:18:59,324 --> 00:19:00,552
- three mutilations...
- Three mutilations...

338
00:19:00,592 --> 00:19:02,287
two stranglings.
General manager Gerald Olin

339
00:19:02,327 --> 00:19:04,454
is well-versed in
the hotel's tragic history,

340
00:19:04,496 --> 00:19:07,294
dryly reciting the docket
of carnage like a bookkeeper

341
00:19:07,332 --> 00:19:09,061
discussing his ledger.

342
00:19:09,101 --> 00:19:11,160
Well, you think
you're clever, don't you?

343
00:19:11,203 --> 00:19:12,534
I know the game.

344
00:19:12,571 --> 00:19:13,970
Well, during
your investigation,

345
00:19:14,005 --> 00:19:16,496
did you discover
the 22 natural deaths

346
00:19:16,541 --> 00:19:18,532
that have occurred
in 1408?

347
00:19:20,312 --> 00:19:21,643
Natural deaths?

348
00:19:21,680 --> 00:19:24,012
Ah, didn't find out
about them

349
00:19:24,049 --> 00:19:27,576
because the newspapers don't
print anything about them.

350
00:19:27,619 --> 00:19:30,952
Hmm. All told,
there have been 56 deaths

351
00:19:30,989 --> 00:19:32,422
in 1408.

352
00:19:32,457 --> 00:19:35,688
56?
You're shitting me.

353
00:19:35,727 --> 00:19:37,524
You don't know anything.

354
00:19:37,562 --> 00:19:40,588
The causes of death
in 1408 range

355
00:19:40,632 --> 00:19:43,066
from heart attack,
stroke, drowning...

356
00:19:43,101 --> 00:19:45,797
- Drowning?
- Yes, one Mr. Grady Miller

357
00:19:45,837 --> 00:19:47,964
drowned
in his chicken soup.

358
00:19:48,006 --> 00:19:50,372
That's hard to do.
How... how did he do that?

359
00:19:50,409 --> 00:19:52,001
How indeed?

360
00:19:52,043 --> 00:19:55,035
Interesting.
It's all in here.

361
00:19:55,080 --> 00:19:58,447
I will let you have this
and give you access to my office.

362
00:19:58,483 --> 00:20:00,815
You can take notes,
put it all in your book.

363
00:20:00,852 --> 00:20:03,047
My only condition

364
00:20:03,088 --> 00:20:06,785
is that you do not
stay in that room.

365
00:20:06,825 --> 00:20:09,521
You'll let me look
at all that stuff?

366
00:20:09,561 --> 00:20:11,552
Hmm.

367
00:20:19,271 --> 00:20:22,240
I never did
get that drink.

368
00:20:27,012 --> 00:20:28,411
(corks pops)

369
00:20:40,859 --> 00:20:44,192
- Oh, that is good.
- Here, keep it.

370
00:20:44,229 --> 00:20:46,254
Compliments
of the house.

371
00:20:57,876 --> 00:20:59,571
- I'm still staying.
- Damn it to hell!

372
00:20:59,611 --> 00:21:01,511
I'm sorry.

373
00:21:01,546 --> 00:21:04,606
All right here.
Here, read the godforsaken thing.

374
00:21:04,649 --> 00:21:06,742
I guarantee you,
once you've read it

375
00:21:06,785 --> 00:21:09,151
you won't want to stay
in 1408.

376
00:21:11,122 --> 00:21:13,386
The first victim:
Mr. Kevin O'Malley,

377
00:21:13,425 --> 00:21:15,222
sewing machine salesman.

378
00:21:15,260 --> 00:21:17,125
Checked into the hotel
the first week it opened...

379
00:21:17,162 --> 00:21:20,097
- October, 1912.
- Cut his own throat, right?

380
00:21:20,131 --> 00:21:21,689
Oh, that's not
the horrific part.

381
00:21:21,733 --> 00:21:23,758
Afterwards, in a fit
of insanity,

382
00:21:23,802 --> 00:21:26,236
he tried to stitch
himself back together

383
00:21:26,271 --> 00:21:28,705
using an old sewing needle
before he bled to death.

384
00:21:28,740 --> 00:21:30,435
Easy, man.

385
00:21:30,475 --> 00:21:33,467
Look, Mr. Enslin,
you don't have to stay in 1408.

386
00:21:33,512 --> 00:21:35,537
You can take
photographs of 1404.

387
00:21:35,580 --> 00:21:39,107
It has the exact same layout and no one
will ever know the difference.

388
00:21:39,150 --> 00:21:41,812
- My readers expect the truth.
- Your readers?

389
00:21:41,853 --> 00:21:44,651
Your readers expect
grotesqueries

390
00:21:44,689 --> 00:21:46,850
and cheap thrills.

391
00:21:46,892 --> 00:21:49,622
"The headless ghost
of Mr. Eugene Rilsby

392
00:21:49,661 --> 00:21:51,424
still walks
his abandoned farmhouse."

393
00:21:51,463 --> 00:21:54,899
"The Barking Phantom
of Mount Hope Cemetery."

394
00:21:54,933 --> 00:21:56,662
A direct quote...
how'd you know that?

395
00:21:56,701 --> 00:21:58,464
Your books aren't
hard to find.

396
00:21:58,503 --> 00:22:00,368
They're on the bargain
shelves

397
00:22:00,405 --> 00:22:03,135
of any paperback
novel store;

398
00:22:03,174 --> 00:22:06,701
full of cynicism,
written by a talented, intelligent man

399
00:22:06,745 --> 00:22:09,407
who doesn't believe
in anything or anyone but himself.

400
00:22:09,447 --> 00:22:12,348
Guilty as charged.

401
00:22:12,384 --> 00:22:15,182
Hey listen, this meeting's over.
Why don't you give me the room?

402
00:22:15,220 --> 00:22:17,711
Oh please, don't act
like a hurt schoolgirl.

403
00:22:17,756 --> 00:22:20,816
- In fact, you surprised me.
- Oh.

404
00:22:20,859 --> 00:22:23,692
You are not
the hack-n-slash I expected.

405
00:22:23,728 --> 00:22:26,322
I rather liked the first one,
the hardcover.

406
00:22:26,364 --> 00:22:30,061
What was it called?
"The Last Walk..."

407
00:22:30,101 --> 00:22:31,398
"Long Road Home."

408
00:22:31,436 --> 00:22:34,405
"The Long Road Home,"
yes.

409
00:22:34,439 --> 00:22:36,907
I rather thought
the father was a bastard.

410
00:22:36,942 --> 00:22:38,842
Yeah, he was.

411
00:22:38,877 --> 00:22:40,902
Um...

412
00:22:40,946 --> 00:22:42,413
Iook man, just
give me the key.

413
00:22:42,447 --> 00:22:45,541
- Mr. Enslin...
- Just give me the key!

414
00:22:45,584 --> 00:22:48,610
Listen, I stayed
at the Bigsby house.

415
00:22:48,653 --> 00:22:51,588
I brushed my goddamn teeth
right next to the tub

416
00:22:51,623 --> 00:22:53,921
where Sir David Smith
drowned his whole family.

417
00:22:53,959 --> 00:22:56,928
And I stopped being afraid
of vampires when I was 12.

418
00:22:56,962 --> 00:23:00,523
Do you know why I can stay
in your spooky old room, Mr. Olin?

419
00:23:00,565 --> 00:23:03,363
Because I know that
ghoulies and ghosties

420
00:23:03,401 --> 00:23:05,699
and long-legged beasties
don't exist.

421
00:23:06,838 --> 00:23:08,328
Even if they did,

422
00:23:08,373 --> 00:23:10,967
there's no God to protect
us from them, is there?

423
00:23:12,711 --> 00:23:14,702
So I can't talk you
out of this?

424
00:23:14,746 --> 00:23:17,306
I think we've reached
an understanding.

425
00:23:17,349 --> 00:23:19,783
Very well.

426
00:23:19,818 --> 00:23:22,378
Come with me.

427
00:23:27,359 --> 00:23:29,452
(jangles)

428
00:23:32,530 --> 00:23:34,191
(elevator dings)

429
00:23:34,232 --> 00:23:36,666
Most hotels have
switched to magnetics.

430
00:23:36,701 --> 00:23:40,137
An actual key.
That's a nice touch... it's antiquey.

431
00:23:40,171 --> 00:23:43,732
We have magnetic cards also, but
electronics don't seem to work in 1408.

432
00:23:43,775 --> 00:23:45,640
Hope you don't have
a pacemaker.

433
00:23:45,677 --> 00:23:48,646
General manager claims that the phantom
in room interferes...

434
00:23:48,680 --> 00:23:50,773
I have never used
the word "phantom."

435
00:23:50,815 --> 00:23:53,283
Oh, I'm sorry.
Spirit? Specter?

436
00:23:53,318 --> 00:23:54,842
No, you misunderstand.

437
00:23:54,886 --> 00:23:57,150
Whatever's in 1408
is nothing like that.

438
00:23:57,188 --> 00:23:59,986
Then what is it?

439
00:24:00,025 --> 00:24:02,459
It's an evil
fucking room.

440
00:24:04,396 --> 00:24:06,523
Please.

441
00:24:10,268 --> 00:24:13,863
Mr. Odin.
(speaks French)

442
00:24:13,905 --> 00:24:16,703
Oh, oui.
Tres bien.

443
00:24:18,510 --> 00:24:20,102
(classical
music playing)

444
00:24:22,180 --> 00:24:24,705
Why don't the owners
just close the room?

445
00:24:26,384 --> 00:24:28,852
The Yasuko Corporation
prefers to pretend there's no problem.

446
00:24:28,887 --> 00:24:31,879
Just as they pretend
there's no 13th floor.

447
00:24:33,525 --> 00:24:35,493
The room,
it's got to be filthy.

448
00:24:35,527 --> 00:24:37,722
I mean, the sheets haven't been changed
in what? 11 years?

449
00:24:37,762 --> 00:24:40,697
No no no,
we're very professional.

450
00:24:40,732 --> 00:24:44,168
1408 gets a light
turn once a month.

451
00:24:44,202 --> 00:24:46,432
I supervise, the maids
work in pairs.

452
00:24:46,471 --> 00:24:49,235
We treat the room
as if it's a chamber

453
00:24:49,274 --> 00:24:50,798
filled with poison gas.

454
00:24:50,842 --> 00:24:54,539
We only stay 10 minutes
and I insist the door remain open.

455
00:24:54,579 --> 00:24:56,945
But still...

456
00:24:59,250 --> 00:25:01,878
A few years ago, a young
maid from El Salvador

457
00:25:01,920 --> 00:25:03,478
found herself locked
in the bathroom.

458
00:25:03,521 --> 00:25:04,749
She was only there
for a few moments,

459
00:25:04,789 --> 00:25:06,780
but when we pulled
her out, she was...

460
00:25:06,825 --> 00:25:09,555
- She was dead.
- No, blind.

461
00:25:09,594 --> 00:25:11,789
She had taken a pair
of scissors

462
00:25:11,830 --> 00:25:13,798
and gouged
her eyes out.

463
00:25:13,832 --> 00:25:16,198
- She was laughing hysterically.
- (bell rings)

464
00:25:16,234 --> 00:25:18,532
- Ouch.
- Your floor.

465
00:25:19,704 --> 00:25:21,331
Well, this is where
we part company.

466
00:25:21,372 --> 00:25:24,603
This is as close
as I get to 1408

467
00:25:24,642 --> 00:25:26,701
unless it's that time
of the month.

468
00:25:28,613 --> 00:25:31,343
- See you tomorrow.
- Mr. Enslin?

469
00:25:31,382 --> 00:25:33,350
Please...

470
00:25:33,384 --> 00:25:35,352
don't do this.

471
00:25:38,590 --> 00:25:40,558
I'll call you about
those Knicks tickets.

472
00:25:40,592 --> 00:25:43,117
(bell rings)

473
00:25:55,507 --> 00:25:57,805
(man speaking loudly)

474
00:26:13,091 --> 00:26:15,252
(TV playing)

475
00:26:17,762 --> 00:26:19,389
(wheel squeaking)

476
00:26:29,808 --> 00:26:31,901
(woman laughing)
Stop it!

477
00:26:42,320 --> 00:26:44,618
(elevator dings)

478
00:26:44,656 --> 00:26:47,489
(classical music
playing)

479
00:27:04,008 --> 00:27:05,976
(flies buzzing)

480
00:27:06,010 --> 00:27:08,171
(baby crying)

481
00:27:10,882 --> 00:27:13,715
Okay. It's okay, sweetie.
We're home now.

482
00:27:13,751 --> 00:27:14,843
Here we go.

483
00:27:21,226 --> 00:27:23,091
(knocks)

484
00:28:19,651 --> 00:28:21,778
This is it?

485
00:28:22,787 --> 00:28:25,449
You got to be kidding me.

486
00:28:41,439 --> 00:28:44,738
Round one goes to the hideous Mr. Olin
for effective aggressiveness.

487
00:28:44,776 --> 00:28:48,109
I have to admit,
he had me going for a moment.

488
00:28:49,380 --> 00:28:52,213
But where is
the bone-chilling terror?

489
00:28:52,250 --> 00:28:55,014
Show me the rivers
of blood.

490
00:29:00,992 --> 00:29:03,460
It's just a room.

491
00:29:03,494 --> 00:29:05,621
(Muzak playing)

492
00:29:14,872 --> 00:29:16,533
(TV turns off)

493
00:29:48,373 --> 00:29:51,638
$8 for beer nuts.

494
00:29:51,676 --> 00:29:54,201
This room is evil.

495
00:29:54,245 --> 00:29:57,305
Mike's voice: Olin said hotels are about
fertile creature comforts.

496
00:29:57,348 --> 00:29:59,646
It's a good line,
but I wonder

497
00:29:59,684 --> 00:30:02,482
whether they're really
about reassuring platitudes,

498
00:30:02,520 --> 00:30:05,011
a prosaic sense
